{\pard\sl-216\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-282\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi299 {\f11\fs19 To accomplish the projects goal of outdoor scene classi cation, the chosen approach fo-cused on di erentiating features for optimal category separation. The constraints of limited resolution and abridged training set were not considered in feature selection. Instead, fea-tures were chosen based on heuristic observations made during the compulsory resolution experiment. The variation in resolutions revealed the rst feature, frequency, as a major component of class identity. Color composition was identi ed as a possible feature after observing its consistency across low resolution test images. The Scale Invariant Feature Transform (SIFT) was used for the last major feature because of its history as a discrim-inating feature among complex scenes. The system design was then based around nding a con guration of these features to produce accurate scene classi cations. To perform the nal classi cation, two options were evaluated; a single layer consisting of dimensionality reduction and a support vector machine and multiple layers, each with their own support vector machine. These two options were chosen based on the variability of the features and relative independence of the classi er and feature selection. As a group of three, the goal was to provide three strongly discriminating features that would be combined to form a system more capable than any sole feature. The results of the independent frequency re-sponse gave clear separation between classes havings high variations in the spatio-frequency domain. Color histograms provided high recognition rates for forest, highway and building classes. The SIFT method also separated forest, highway and building classes accurately. Gabor lters served well by themselves but not when in conjunction with other classes.}\par}
}\sect\sbknone
