{{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f3\fs29 1 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f3\fs29 \qj\fi-480\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx480\faauto\ls2\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin480\itap0 {\plain\f3\fs29 Introduction }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-306\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-313\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Scene recognition in image processing not only consists of recognizing the objects, but also their holistic composition that forms the scene. While detection of individual objects helps in classifying a scene to some degree, the relationship between the objects is major deciding factor in scene classi cation. Identi cation of man-made objects, and describing the scene according to their functional representation is an easier task than labeling a natural scene, which consists of multiple, ambiguous object classes and varying object to object relationships. This study takes an aim multiple feature sets produced from natural and arti cal feature classi cation methods. To obtain such classi cation, we use Gabor Features for object detection and feature space separation. Gabor features, described by Gabor lters}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-245\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\ql{\f3\fs29 2  Methods}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-306\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-307\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Each feature was investigated independently before being combined with other features. Fea-tures were evaluated using statistical methods as well as individual classi cation results. Statis-tical evidence was gathered primarily from the training set as inclusive or exclusive validation runs. This would provide further insight into how the feature would perform against similar images or how well the feature generalizes its training set. Classi cation results were generated from a exclusive subset of the training set as well as the test set.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-111\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-304\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs22 The Gabor feature extraction consists of (1) designing a set of Gabor lters in the spatio-frequency domain[4], and (2) forming a bank of lters to be applied to the images for feature matching [2]. While step (1) makes sure that optimal lters are designed to match feature variablity of natural and man made objects, in step (2) we decide the ideal lter parameters in a set of Gabor lters and form a lter bank. The goal is to produce feature vectors that}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-73\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\ql{\f2\fs22 describe the scene as accurarately as possible.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-370\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\ql{\f14\fs24 2.1  Gabor Filters}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-243\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-304\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Gabor lters have long been used for texture detection, segmentation and texture synthesis. The reason for their popularity is because they seem to mimic the characteristics of cells in the visual cortex of macaca and cats [3] [1]. Appropriate Gabor lters can approximate these characteristics. Mathematically, a Gabor lter of a particular orientation and frequency is a sinusoid modulated by a Gaussian:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-292\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li3440\ql{\f15\fs22 h{(}x; y{) =} s{(}x; y{)}g{(}x; y{)}}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-327\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl274\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Where {s}({x; y} is a sinusoidal plane and {g}({x; y}) is a 2-D Gausssian. The Gaussian is represented by:}\par}
}
