\margl1440\margr1446\margt1440\margb522\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\cols1\colno1\colw9020
{\pard\sl-56\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-271\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\ql{\f2\fs22 A Gabor lter in 2 dimensions can thus be used to approximate the frequency and spatial response of the di erent classes.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-362\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f8\fs22 2.1.1 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f8\fs22 \qj\fi-760\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx760\faauto\ls3\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin760\itap0 \sl239\slmult1 {\plain\f8\fs22 Gabor Filter Bank }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-250\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-316\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs21 A lter bank of 3 orientation and 8 frequencies was considered for feature extraction, giving a total of 24 lters for feature vector creation. Images from each class in the test set was convolved with the lter bank to give a 256x1 feature vector. The criterion of selecting particular frequen-cies was mostly based on the natural dissimilarity and the apparent inter-class separation. For example, features belonging to a set of natural images, like coast, appears considerably di erent than a set of arti cial images, such as tall buildings. It was hypothesized that the feature set resulting from the ltered images would obtain a greater inter-class separation, while relying on other methods (explained) below for local feature extraction and intra-class separation. As the following table shows, the intra-class separation is not so prevalant with just the use of Gabor lter bank, while good separation is achieved between the classes. It should be mentioned that classes such a forest, which depict a uniform frequency distribution, are the ones best separated from other classes. On the other hand, coast does not perform well owing to sparse frequency distribution and many low frequency, blended features:}\par}
