{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f8\fs22 2.1.3 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f8\fs22 \qj\fi-760\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx760\faauto\ls5\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin760\itap0 \sl239\slmult1 {\plain\f8\fs22 Power Spectrum Density }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-250\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl301\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Power spectrum provides the higher-order statistics of natural images, and helps represent the neuronic activity in the visual system and our adaptation to it. To measure the power spec-turum density, a simple Fourier Transformation to convert an image from space to frequency domain of each testing image was calculated, and was then shifted to a zero frequency in the middle. Square of the modulus of the Fourier transformation gives us the power spectrum den-sity.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-48\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl297\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 The power spectrum of each each was contrast-normalized, to give a measure of total neigbour-hood activity in its region. This was achieved by convoluting a power spectrum image with a Gaussian (for a Gaussian Neighbourhood representation) and dividing by its squar. The result achieved was the following:}\par}
