{\pard\sl-249\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-315\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Template matching is a Computer Vision technique that segments the image according to a pre-de ned reponse value, which is a template derived from either the target image itself or a set of images. This template is then applied to the target image to gure out the relation between the two. This relation is more of the similarity or dissimilarity in behaviour of the two images rather than the the di er- ence in the value of pixels. The output image is then mapped over to the original image to locate the relationship measure, which in this case are tree crowns. This technique is mathematically known as cross-correlation. Gray-level cross correlation is de ned by: orrelation computes a numerical index which indicates how accurately or behaviorally the template matches the image in that position on a pixel by pixel basis. Mathematically, correlation is the degree to which two variables agree by behaviour. Correlation for gray level images can be computed using the following equation:}\par}
}
