{\pard\sl-286\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f3\fs29 3 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f3\fs29 \qj\fi-480\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx480\faauto\ls7\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin480\itap0 {\plain\f3\fs29 Color Histograms }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-306\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-307\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 As a perceptual feature, color composition had a clear impact on the separation between the chosen classes of outdoor scenes during the resolution experiment. As a method for scene classi cation, color information is historically one of the oldest machine recognized features [6]. The simplest method presented for scene categorization used a non-linear mapping of the RGB color space and histogram intersection [7]; this provided adequate separation between indoor and outdoor scenes.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-111\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-314\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 To classify di erent types of outdoor scenes, a similar approach was considered. Each of the training images was separated into 16 equally sized blocks, a clear advantage of the single square resolution of the image set. Once the blocks were separated, the inner four and bottom two blocks were averaged across each class to create a template. The template would then contain both color and limited spacial information. The selection of the middle and bottom blocks allowed any noise on the edge of the image or any non-discriminating features such as the sky to be removed from the average. The average block histograms were then used to compute the histogram intersection with each test image. The resulting histogram intersection, still partitioned into blocks, along with the test images histogram was concatenated and passed into a support vector machine for classi cation.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-373\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f14\fs24 3.1 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f14\fs24 \qj\fi-620\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx620\faauto\ls8\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin620\itap0 {\plain\f14\fs24 Results }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-243\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-297\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 The results of the color histogram test are organized by color space. The results listed below are the number of mis-classi cations (false positives & false negatives) over 150 test images with 30 test images per class. The number of principle components as well as the SVM kernels are listed as parameters.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-314\slmult0\par

