{\pard\sl-152\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li340\sl-253\slmult0 \ql{\f2\fs22 The combination of other features will further improve the  nal classi cation.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-244\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f3\fs29 4 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f3\fs29 \qj\fi-480\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx480\faauto\ls9\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin480\itap0 \sl239\slmult1 {\plain\f3\fs29 SIFT Features }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-307\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-304\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 SIFT-Based features were investigated and implemented as another source of image features for separation between the classes. There are two main reasons SIFT was chosen- rstly, it is well established and has been demonstrated to result in meaningful, distinct data. Secondly, the multiple kinds of data retrieved from SIFT (both the patch descriptors and the location data) gives multiple avenues to explore for features.}\par}
}\sect\sbknone
\marglsxn5900\margrsxn5900\cols1\colno1\colw100
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-215\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\ql{\f2\fs17 8}\par}
}\sect\sbkpage\sectd\pard\plain
\pgwsxn11900\pghsxn16838
{\*\bkmkstart page10}{\*\bkmkend page10}
\margl1440\margr1446\margt1440\margb534{\phpg\posx4345\pvpg\posy7378\absw1088\absh1253 \par}{\phpg\posx4300\pvpg\posy8188\absw1100\absh151\ql\sl185\slmult1 \f15\fs17 D{(}A; B{) =}\par}
\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\cols1\colno1\colw9020
{\pard\sl-3\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f14\fs24 4.1 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f14\fs24 \qj\fi-620\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx620\faauto\ls10\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin620\itap0 {\plain\f14\fs24 Bag of Words }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-243\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-307\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 The rst method investigated was a simple bag of words approach. This is a well-tested method that has performed well in the past, and fairly simple to implement. Firstly, SIFT Feature Descriptors are generated for each of the images in the entire training set, with no separation between classes. These are clustered to N di erent groups using k-means clustering. The end result of this is the Dictionary of words that will be used to generate and count the bag of words.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-111\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl301\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 The feature vector generated from an individual image is a count of the matched words between the SIFT points on the image and the clustered points in the dictionary. Each of the SIFT descriptors found in a given image is matched to one of the cluster centers by simple 1-nearest neighbor. The index of the matching cluster is then taken, and the corresponding index in the bag is incremented. The end result is taken as the feature vector for later combination with the other feature sets.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-48\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-298\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 The di culty with this approach was to decide the number of clusters (or words) to create during the k-means clustering. As such, dictionaries were generated with 16, 32, 64, 128, and 256 clusters. With these dictionaries, the feature vectors were generated for each of the testing images. Once the feature vectors were computed, the average distance between each vector, and every vector of another class, was computed. This is de ned as:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-288\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li4020\sl-494\slmult0 \ql{\f20\fs16 {\fs31 \super m}{\fs31 \sub j}{\fs31 \sub =1}  {\fs31 \super n}{\fs31 \sub i}{\fs31 \sub =1}{\fs43 \f26 \super j}{\fs43 \super F}A;i   {\fs43 \super F}B;j{\fs43 \f26 \super j}}\par}
}{\shp{\*\shpinst\shpfhdr0\shpbxcolumn\shpbypara\shpwr3\shpfblwtxt1\shpz1\shpleft4013\shptop-52\shpright6096\shpbottom-52{\sp{\sn shapeType}{\sv 20}}
{\sp{\sn fBehindDocument}{\sv 1}}
{\sp{\sn fFlipH}{\sv 0}}
{\sp{\sn fFlipV}{\sv 0}}
{\sp{\sn lineWidth}{\sv 5537}}
{\sp{\sn lineColor}{\sv 0}}
{\sp{\sn lineDashing}{\sv 0}}}}

{
{\pard\plain \li4960\sl194\slmult1 \ql{\f15\fs22 ij}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-109\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-302\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 Where {F}{\fs31 \sub A;i}, is the {i}th feature vector of an arbitrary class A, {F}{\fs31 \sub B;j}, is the ith feature vector of an arbitrary class B (which may be identical to class A), {n} is the cardinality of class A, and {m} is the cardinality of class B. This gives a rough sense of the separation between the two di erent classes (or, in the case of A=B, the spread of the class).}\par}
}{\shp{\*\shpinst\shpfhdr0\shpbxcolumn\shpbypara\shpwr3\shpfblwtxt1\shpz1\shpleft1317\shptop266\shpright7707\shpbottom266{\sp{\sn shapeType}{\sv 20}}
