{\pard\sl-247\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-311\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs22 From the gathered data, it was decided that 64 clusters would be optimal for the separation between classes- while the distances were not the absolute highest, the inter-class distances were on average higher in relation to the intra-class distances (the class spreads), indicating that 64 clusters gave the best separation between classes. The class separation was also considered to be su cient for this method to be used in the classi er. Speci cally, most classes were found to have good separation between themselves and the other classes, with the exception of tall buildings- this class, for all cluster sizes, generally had higher spread than distance to other classes.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-239\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-298\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs21 An additional modi er to this method was also examined. The feature vectors were nor-malized before the distances were calculated, in an e ort to examine the distances between the general patterns of the feature vectors rather than their absolute values. However, this resulted in worse separation across all examined cluster counts, so the method was discarded.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-109\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-304\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs22 As a precursor to the nal classi cations using all feature vectors, the Bag of Words was evaluated as a single feature vector for classi cation. An SVM was trained for each class, using the 70 training images in that class as positive training data, and all other training images as negative training data. The following confusion matrix is the raw output from the SVMs, including classi cations that returned multiple positive results:}\par}
}\sect\sbknone
