{\pard\plain \li0\sl-271\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\ql\fi339 {\f2\fs22 However, due to the nature of the nal classi er (combining information from multiple sources of features), this non-speci city is not as large an issue.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-371\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f14\fs24 4.2 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f14\fs24 \qj\fi-620\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx620\faauto\ls11\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin620\itap0 {\plain\f14\fs24 SIFT Density Feature }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-243\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-297\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs22 The other SIFT-based feature that was examined was a method of determining a pro le of the density of SIFT feature points that occurred in an image. It was hoped that this would result in separation between busier scenes (tall buildings, forest) and smoother, less busy scenes (highways, coasts).}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-112\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-304\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs22 The method is as follows: After the SIFT features are computed, the image is split into a number of bins, NxN on each side. The number of SIFT feature points that fall within each bin are counted, and entered into a histogram. This histogram is the nal feature vector. The size of this binning was tested at 4x4, 8x8, 16x16 and 32x32. However, all of the results looked similar to the following:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-168\slmult0\par

