{\pard\sl-284\slmult0\par
{{\listtext{\pard\plain {\f3\fs29 6 }\tab}}\pard\plain 
\f3\fs29 \qj\fi-480\nowidctlpar\jclisttab\tx480\faauto\ls15\ilvl0\rin0\nooverflow\lin480\itap0 \sl239\slmult1 {\plain\f3\fs29 Conclusion }\par}
}
{\pard\sl-307\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-307\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj{\f2\fs21 As evidenced by the results of the combined and hierarchical classi er, the features selected had overlapping performance characteristics. For classes like forest, highway, and building, all classi ers performed relatively well (90%+ accuracy); but for the problematic classes of coast and mountain, no feature alone or combined produced noticeably better classi cation decisions. This result shows that di erent features can arrive at the same classi cation accuracy and that unique feature selection alone cannot ensure that each class will be adequately separated.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-110\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-303\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs20 The problem lies in the visual structure of the class, where no feature could extract a unique response for nondescript or highly variable classes. This is clearly the problem with coast and mountain, where the visual features alone are so varied that without semantic knowledge, many scenes in the same class would be considered very di erent. The color of the coasts varies greatly depending on how much of the beach is visible and the variation of the water and sky colors.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-112\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl297\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs22 The mountain class included calm snow covered mountains as well as mountains in forests and near rivers, which would confuse any collection of interest points with the wide range of settings. Frequency was again fooled by the noisiness of the scene, where noisy scenes could be part of any particular class and could not be separated.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-49\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl-304\slmult0 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi339 {\f2\fs22 The system performed scene classi cation on three of the ve classes exceptionally well for using a straightforward approach for feature selection and classi cation, and was able to out-perform random chance on the remaining two classes. For a future improvement, some semantic information could be included to help classify coast and mountain scenes based on low level cues from the features explored in this system.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-200\slmult0\par
\pard\sl-242\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\ql{\f3\fs29 References}\par}
}
